Base of Operations.Other Known Chapters:
The Order of Blue Fire was active in many other places across Faerûn, including:
*[[Baldur's Gate]]. The Order maintained a mission in [[Scarred Alley]], which was connected to other houses via a ''[[teleportation circle]]''.{{Cite organized play/LFR/Silent Streets and Vanished Souls|12}}{{Cite organized play/LFR/Silent Streets and Vanished Souls|13}} This chapter was abandoned by the Order after subversive actions by [[Grand Duke]] [[Valarken]].
*[[Halruaa]]. The so-called [[Temple of Blue Fire]] on [[Mount Talath]] was vigorously defended by Order forces at the fortress of [[Talathgard]].
*[[Impiltur]]. The Order's more sinister activities in this realm were known to [[Arshryke Taranth]], the royal spymaster of Impiltur, who worked hard to foil their machinations.
* [[Marsember]]. This chapter was established in the early-to-mid 15{{th}} century DR, and over the following decades, it handled several outbreaks of Spellplague and assisted thousands of patients with their spellscars.{{Cite LFR/CORM1-4/All the King's Men|13}}
*[[Sshamath]]. [[Drow]] members of the Order established the [[School of Blue Fire]] in this city.{{Cite LFR/CORE2-1/Killing the Messenger|18,20}}

document_data.Dogma:
[[File:Sharn cultist 4e.jpg|thumb|300px|''A member of the Order of Blue Flame seeks guidance from a sharn.'']]
The secret faith of the Order of Blue Fire was based on the teachings of its true leaders: crazed [[sharn]]s and a mysterious entity known as the [[Masters of Absolute Accord]], and their deepest precepts further regarded the Spellplague and its energies as a [[god|divine being]], of which the sharns were said to be miraculous manifestations.

Owing to the scattered organization of the Order and the sometimes contradictory edicts of the sharns and the Masters of Absolute Accord, it was not uncommon for different houses of the Order to evolve in different ways, and in some cases, schisms arose as different sects believed that the Order's dogma could be pursued in different&mdash;even truly benevolent&mdash;ways. For example, the chapter in Marsember taught that the Spellplague was part of the natural world, and that spellscars were "gifts" not to be cured but to be controlled and understood.{{Cite LFR/CORE2-1/Killing the Messenger|56}}

document_data.History:
Originally founded during the [[Wailing Years]] as a cult dedicated to prolonging the Spellplague, the Order first came to prominence in the {{YearlinkName|1393}}, when it started aiding scar pilgrims in Ormpetarr.

Following the events of the [[Ruining]] in [[Neverwinter]], a group of Blue Fire fanatics traveled to the [[Cathedral of Mystra (Neverwinter)|Cathedral of Mystra]] within Neverwinter's [[Chasm]] upon hearing rumors of active Spellplague within. There, they clashed with [[Scar Company]], a division within the [[Neverwinter Guard]] who battled the [[plaguechanged]] horrors within the Chasm.

As of {{Yearlink|1479}},{{4e-time}} agents of the Order operating in the [[North]] heard rumors about active Spellplague in the village of [[Deadsnows]], and sought to hire [[adventurer]]s to investigate.{{Cite organized play/LFR/Shades of Blue Fire|5}} They were similarly interested in rumors of a plaguechanged [[wight]] known as the [[Mound King]].{{Cite organized play/LFR/Shades of Blue Fire|26}}
